      <!-- ═══ ACCESSIBILITY TAB ═══ -->
      <div class="tab-content" id="tab-accessibility" style="display: none; padding-top: 32px;">
        <h2 id="accessibility-overview" class="doc-section-title">Accessibility</h2>
        <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Guidelines for ensuring all tag interactions are accessible across assistive technologies.</p>

        <!-- Color Contrast -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="color-contrast" class="doc-h3">Color Contrast<span class="h3-badge" style="background: rgba(34,197,94,0.15); color: #16a34a;">WCAG AA Pass</span></h3>
          <p class="doc-section-subtitle">All filled tag variants meet WCAG 2.1 AA contrast ratio requirements (4.5:1 for text). The tinted background and darker foreground text combination ensures legibility across all semantic variants.</p>
          <div style="margin-top: 24px; padding: 16px 20px; background: rgba(34,197,94,0.05); border: 1px solid rgba(34,197,94,0.2); border-radius: 12px; display: flex; gap: 12px; align-items: flex-start;">
             <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#16a34a" stroke-width="2" style="flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 2px;"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle><path d="M12 16v-4"></path><path d="M12 8h.01"></path></svg>
             <p style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--prism-text); line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;"><strong>WCAG 2.1 Level AA:</strong> All UEMS Tag variants use tinted backgrounds with high-contrast foreground text, meeting the minimum <strong>4.5:1</strong> contrast ratio for normal text.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <!-- Keyboard Navigation -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="keyboard-navigation" class="doc-h3">Keyboard Navigation</h3>
          <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Tags and their close buttons are fully keyboard accessible.</p>
          <ul class="doc-list">
            <li><strong>Tab:</strong> Tags are focusable via the Tab key, allowing keyboard users to navigate to them.</li>
            <li><strong>Close button focus:</strong> The close button is independently focusable, so users can dismiss a tag without affecting adjacent elements.</li>
            <li><strong>Focus indicator:</strong> A visible focus ring is displayed around the tag or close button when focused.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <!-- Screen Reader -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="screen-reader" class="doc-h3">Screen Reader</h3>
          <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Ensure tag content and actions are properly announced to screen readers.</p>
          <ul class="doc-list">
            <li><strong>Label text:</strong> The tag label is read as text content by screen readers.</li>
            <li><strong>Close button:</strong> The close button should have an accessible label such as "Remove [tag name]" to clearly communicate its purpose.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <!-- RTL Accessibility -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="rtl-accessibility" class="doc-h3">RTL Accessibility</h3>
          <ul class="doc-list">
            <li>Full RTL support with mirrored layout ensures the tag reads naturally in right-to-left languages.</li>
            <li>The localized RTL Label property provides proper text content for assistive technologies in RTL contexts.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <hr class="doc-divider" />

        <!-- Disabled State -->
        <div class="doc-section">
          <h3 id="disabled-state" class="doc-h3">Disabled State</h3>
          <ul class="doc-list">
            <li>Disabled tags are excluded from the tab order, preventing keyboard users from focusing on non-interactive elements.</li>
            <li>The disabled state is conveyed to assistive technology via <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">aria-disabled="true"</code>, ensuring screen readers communicate the inactive state.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

